'''Lis Brack-Bernsen''' (born 1946) is a Danish and Swiss mathematician, [[history of science|historian of science]], and [[history of mathematics|historian of mathematics]], known for her work on [[Babylonian astronomy]]. She is an [[Academic ranks in Germany|extraordinary professor]] of the history of science at the [[University of Regensburg]].
==Education and career== Brack-Bernsen was born in [[Copenhagen]] on March 2, 1946.{{r|cv}} She earned a diploma in mathematics with a minor in physics from the [[University of Copenhagen]] in 1970,{{r|cv}} with Olaf Schmidt as a mentor,{{r|ih}} and completed her Ph.D. in the history of mathematics in 1974 at the [[University of Basel]], also with studies at [[Stony Brook University]]. Her dissertation was ''Die Basler Mayatafeln; astronomische Deutung der Inschriften auf den Türstürzen 2 und 3 aus Tempel IV in Tikal'', and was promoted by J. O. Fleckenstein.{{r|cv}}
She worked as a lecturer at the University of Copenhagen for 1974–1975, as a researcher at Stony Brook University from 1975 to 1977, and as a researcher in Grenoble and Regensburg from 1977 to 1979.{{r|cv}} However, at this time she left research to raise a family.{{r|ih}}
In 1997 she completed her [[habilitation]] at [[Goethe University Frankfurt]]. She worked as a ''[[privatdozent]]in'' at Goethe University until 1999, when she moved to the University of Regensburg.{{r|cv}}
==Recognition== Brack-Bernsen was elected to the [[Academy of Sciences Leopoldina]] in 2009.{{r|ih|leo}}
A [[festschrift]], ''Studies on the Ancient Exact Sciences in Honour of Lis Brack-Bernsen'' (John Steele and Mathieu Ossendrijver, eds.) was published by Edition Topoi in 2017.{{r|fs}}
