{{italic title}}
In mathematics, the '''''Zahlbericht''''' (number report) was a report on [[algebraic number theory]] by {{harvs|txt|last=Hilbert|authorlink=David Hilbert|year1=1897|year2=1998|loc2=(English translation)}}.

==History==
In 1893 the German mathematical society invited Hilbert and [[Hermann Minkowski|Minkowski]] to write reports on the theory of numbers. They agreed that Minkowski would cover the more elementary parts of number theory while Hilbert would cover algebraic number theory. Minkowski eventually abandoned his report, while Hilbert's report was published in 1897. It was reprinted in volume 1 of his collected works, and republished in an English translation in 1998.
{{harvtxt|Corry|1996}} and {{harvtxt|Schappacher|2005}} and the English introduction to {{harv|Hilbert|1998}} give detailed discussions of the history and influence of Hilbert's ''Zahlbericht''. 

Some earlier reports on number theory include the report by [[H. J. S. Smith]] in 6 parts between 1859 and 1865, reprinted in {{harvtxt|Smith|1965}}, and the report by {{harvtxt|Brill|Noether|1894}}. {{harvs|txt|last=Hasse|year1=1926|year2=1927|year3=1930}} wrote an update of Hilbert's Zahlbericht that covered [[class field theory]] (republished in 1 volume as {{harv|Hasse|1970}}).

==Contents==
Part 1 covers the theory of general [[number field]]s, including ideals, [[discriminant]]s, differents, units, and ideal classes. 

Part 2 covers [[Galois extension|Galois number field]]s, including in particular [[Hilbert's theorem 90]].

Part 3 covers [[quadratic number field]]s, including the theory of genera, and [[Ideal class group|class number]]s of quadratic fields.

Part 4 covers [[cyclotomic field]]s, including the [[Kronecker–Weber theorem]] (theorem 131), the [[Hilbert–Speiser theorem]] (theorem 132), and the [[Eisenstein reciprocity law]] for ''l''th power residues (theorem 140) .

Part 5 covers [[Kummer extension|Kummer number fields]], and ends with Kummer's proof of Fermat's last theorem for [[regular prime]]s.

